Some specific ways we maintained good progress throughout the semester was mainly due to the different earlier deadlines. Additionally, since at least a few group members tried meeting after class most of the time, we always were slowly progressing since we would discuss any assignments and tasks together and knew what needed to be done. The positive effect that this success can have on a team going forward is that we all feel comfortable with each other and respect one another. After working on a team where there is a good environment that stays on task and makes good progress, each one of us can bring those skills to benefit future teams moving forward.

column11: Our team achieved the goal of creating a functional, lightweight, and affordable light therapy outfit for treating neonatal jaundice. The design allows babies to stay clothed and close to their caregivers while receiving effective phototherapy, addressing key issues with existing solutions.
column12: I successfully contributed to the creation of a functional light therapy outfit by sewing the LED layer, organizing the wiring, and troubleshooting prototype issues. I also supported the team by writing the assessment of the design section and preparing questions for stakeholder interviews.
column26: Our team worked effectively to divide responsibilities based on individual strengths, ensuring that each aspect of the project was completed on time. One specific thing the team did well was maintaining clear and open communication throughout the process, which helped us address challenges quickly and stay aligned with our shared goals. A practice I would bring to my next team.
column27: One thing I would do differently on the next team is establish more frequent check-ins to monitor progress and address potential delays earlier. This would help ensure that all tasks are completed on schedule and avoid last-minute challenges.
column28:
A specific moment when clear communication made a difference for our team was during the wiring troubleshooting phase of the prototype. While spending over four hours at Jacobs, I took the lead in organizing and troubleshooting the wiring system, while the team contributed ideas and suggestions. Together, we managed to successfully assemble the outfit and put it on the baby doll. However, when the outfit was inverted and placed on the doll, several wires became detached, requiring additional troubleshooting. Through open collaboration and problem-solving as a team, we reconnected the wires and ensured the prototype was functional.

This experience highlighted the importance of teamwork and communication in overcoming technical challenges. By actively involving all team members in the process, we were able to address issues quickly and achieve a working prototype. This practice not only enhanced the quality of the project but also strengthened our ability to collaborate under pressure.
column29:
To implement frequent check-ins in my next team, I would suggest scheduling short, structured meetings at least twice a week, either in person or virtually. These meetings would focus on each member providing a quick update on their progress, challenges, and next steps. To ensure these check-ins are effective, I would propose using a shared agenda where team members can document updates and questions beforehand, keeping the meetings focused and time-efficient. Additionally, assigning a rotating facilitator could help ensure everyone stays on track and feels involved.

This approach would improve overall team effectiveness by promoting accountability, identifying potential issues early, and fostering better collaboration. Frequent updates would ensure that everyone is aligned with the shared goals and timelines, reducing last-minute stress and enabling smoother progress toward project milestones. These check-ins would also create a supportive environment where team members feel more comfortable seeking help and sharing ideas.

column28:
Our team worked on the prototype in a collaborative setting that emphasized brainstorming, rapid iteration, and testing. We began by identifying the needs of our target users--individuals with shaky hands who could benefit from an assistive writing device. From initial concept sketches to our first physical prototype, we focused on aligning goals and addressing core functionalities.

The design process involved several key steps. Through brainstorming and research, we identified essential features such as comfort and stability, with each team member contributing unique ideas. After building the initial prototype, we tested it and observed issues like grip instability and weight distribution. Feedback from mock users and advisors guided refinements, such as redistributing weight and improving pen support. Each iteration included redesigning in CAD, reprinting, and retesting, with team members alternating responsibilities to ensure diverse perspectives. Detailed documentation kept us organized throughout.

The iterative process significantly boosted our success. It enhanced collaboration by leveraging each member's strengths and improved communication through shared decision-making. Repeated testing ensured a user-centered design that effectively addressed key needs. Finally, working through challenges together strengthened team dynamics and trust. This process not only resulted in a functional prototype but also highlighted the power of teamwork and adaptability.
column29:
Assigning specific roles can help a team work more efficiently by providing clarity and structure. When each member knows their responsibilities, it minimizes confusion, reduces overlap in tasks, and ensures that critical areas are covered. For instance, one member might focus on research, another on data analysis, and a third on documentation. This specialization allows each person to work on tasks aligned with their strengths, speeding up progress and enhancing the quality of work. Additionally, clear roles foster accountability, as everyone understands what they are expected to contribute and can take ownership of their tasks.

Addressing issues sooner, while essential, can be challenging. One difficulty is that team members may hesitate to raise concerns, fearing conflict or disrupting group harmony. There's also the possibility of miscommunication or differing perspectives, which can delay resolution. To overcome these challenges, the team would need to create a culture of open communication where constructive feedback is welcomed, and issues are framed as opportunities for improvement rather than criticism. Encouraging regular check-ins and fostering trust can also make it easier to tackle problems early.

Clearer timelines and regular reviews would have a significant positive impact on team performance. Timelines help the team stay organized and focused, breaking the project into manageable steps and ensuring steady progress. By knowing deadlines for each phase, team members can plan their work more effectively and avoid last-minute stress. Meanwhile, reviewing assignments before submission ensures the quality of work is high and aligns with team goals. It also provides an opportunity for collaboration, as members can offer suggestions and catch potential errors. Together, these strategies create a more efficient and cohesive workflow, ultimately leading to stronger outcomes and a more unified team.

column29:
It was understood by the members that the down period of communication was temporary due to other class commitments and external factors. However, now looking back, I did feel as though I had a somewhat unfair burden with regards to being the primary person working on the code and technical deliverables for both labs. In both cases, I completed drafts of the code and figures well before the deadlines and requested my group to check and provide feedback. However, I would get no response for days and the team would have to scramble to finish assignments during our short team meetings instead of working on the project. 

It became apparent that the report was started last minute, and we had to help complete and facilitate that process beyond what was agreed upon in terms of work division. In the end we still had to submit the report late. Furthermore, we had a lot of communication issues throughout the last weeks of the semester. I tried to communicate with the group to find times to meet to create the prototype and plan out our next deliverables, but on multiple occasions I was either left on read for days or meeting times were not respected (30min - 1hr delays) where certain members had to leave early to go to work commitments.

I think to improve accountability would require me to bring these concerns up earlier in the semester to set a group standard. The main reason that I did not is that up until now I did not realize or come to think regarding my share of the work compared to the other group. Potentially involving the instructor earlier on and asking group members to hold better accountability and responsibility towards the times we booked for us to work on this project. If we had better communication and more time, I am confident that we would have been able to create a more cohesive and comprehensive prototype and accompanying report.

column26: Our communication and efficiency made meetings and task delegation an extremely smooth-sailing process. This is something some of my other groups, including myself, had struggled with in the past; however through this project and team, we were able to make good progress due to our ability to clearly communicate and work time efficiently.
column27: Our team mainly made plans on a weekly basis as we had weekly meetings on Mondays to decide what to accomplish before the next meeting. While this worked in keeping up with the check-in assignments set by the professor, it didn't leave us with too much time to rapidly iterate through the print, test, and improvement phase of our project. Going forward, having a tentative project timeline that we set at the start of the semester will help us better prepare and make adjustments as we go along.
column28:
Our meetings were always about 50 minutes long and we never really had the need to go beyond that time as each meeting lead came in with a set agenda that helped keep our meeting on track. Every meeting followed an effective template that started with everyone checking in how each other's week had gone during Berkeley time. Once we started our meeting at Berkeley time, we would always take about 10 minutes to share each individuals progress on previously delegated tasks to determine what needs to be done. From there, we would discuss the next deliverable, the expectations of the upcoming deliverable, what decisions need to be made during the meeting, what tasks need to be done by when, and who is in charge of each task. This discussion would never take more than 20-30 minutes. From there, our last 10 minutes would consist of clarifying questions and ensuring that everyone is on the same page. 

Detailed notes regarding the content of the meeting were taken on google docs by that week's notetaker. At the end of each meeting, the team lead/notetaker would send a TLDR on our messages group chat which helped clear any lingering confusion regarding task delegation. This truly helped us ensure that everyone is on the same page and that we are able to make decisions rapidly, enabling efficient progress.
column29:
I had this realization when we had our meeting (Monday of thanksgiving break) to get our Lofi prototype deliverable ready the week before it was due. Our Monday meeting went efficiently as usual and we were able to get out lofi prototype submission done comfortably. However, we weren't aware of the changing and unpredictable turnaround times for 3D printing at our local 3D printing centers. Some of the prints could take up to as long as 4-5 days, leaving us with a matter of few days to test our prototype and probably not enough time to 3D print an improved version. 

With this uncertainty, we were pretty panicked about finding alternative places to 3D print (such as asking family/friends, people on reddit, and exploring my high school's 3D printing facilities). The Jacobs 3D printing facility ended up working out since we had caught it on a low-traffic day the first time, however, our second print took about 3-4 days.

I feel like if we had established a timeline before, we may have realized sooner that we needed to finish our 3D models sooner in order to give us more leg room for additional prints and testing.

column29: The specific situations where a lack of a timeline was felt the most was during the beginning of the construction for our functional prototype. In the future we could have stricter deadlines or deadlines that are set earlier into the start of the project rather than later, because we spent too much time coming up with the manufacturing plan rather than acting on it. column11: Our team's shared goal was to create a device that was efficient in solving poor posture. We were able to develop a device that is easily integratabtle into daily life while providing valid feedback for users.
column12: This class has allowed me to work with a hands on project while learning new skills from my teammates. I was able to lead our team to creating an almost marketable device. I am proud of the work that I put in to accomplish our project goals.
column26: Our team did a great job on communicating things that needed to be done and offering to help those who may need more hands. I really liked how different people in our group would ask questions in order to better our project and design process.
column27: I think our team could have done a better job of distributing and understanding roles in the project. I think often work fell on specific members of the group.
column28: We used a group chat for communication amongst group members. People were very responsible in terms of asking questions, answering questions, filling out when2meets for meetings, etc. I thought this made a difference in the success of our group as there was not much time when our group was in limbo. There was always something being done allowing for our group to be on task. Effective communication played a major role when Joe needed help on the circuitry design so over thanksgiving break he asked us to research if circuits other than a DC would be better for our design
column29: I think our issue with distributing roles evenly came from not understanding what everyone's strong points were. Especially being partnered with a bunch of mechanical engineers they all have very similar skills but did not want to take charge of certain areas. Being a bioengineering major, I took the role of using my knowledge about biomechanics to integrate a design that worked well with postural kyphosis. It was also hard to distribute roles with the hardware because the hardware couldn't be split up, so therefore Joe was often the one working directly with the electronics. I think this made it hard because people wanted to help out but didn't know how to. Uneven distribution was definitely not intentional it was just hard with the components of our project. An even role distribution would have been more helpful, but I think our group did the best we could.
